Histamine in Organs and its Relation to the Sympathetic Nerve Supply.
items.abstract: <jats:title>Summary.</jats:title><jats:p>Large differences occur in the amount of histamine in various organs of the cow as of the sheep.</jats:p><jats:p>A certain relation is apparent between the noradrenaline and histamine amounts in an organ and in the corresponding sympathetic nerve in the cow (Table 2).</jats:p><jats:p>The histamine content of sheep's nerves is considerably lower than that of the corresponding nerves in the cow.</jats:p><jats:p>The histamine and noradrenaline content of sheep nerves run roughly parallel. No such parallelism is found in organs (Table 3).</jats:p><jats:p>Sectioning of the sympathetic nerves to various organs in the sheep was followed by a moderate reduction in the histamine content of the spleen but did not alter the histamine amount in the salivary glands or in the kidney.</jats:p>
